<HL>
   Norwest Holds Talks
   On Possible Purchase
   Of Denver Bank Firm
</HL>
<DATE>
07/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   NOB UBKS
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   MINNEAPOLIS -- Norwest Corp. is holding discussions with
United Banks of Colorado Inc. over a possible acquisition of
the Denver bank-holding concern.
   In a joint release, the companies said "no definitive
agreement has been reached," and cautioned there is "no
assurance" a deal will be struck.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Rumors the company might be the recipient of a bid sent
United Banks of Colorado shares upward on unusually heavy
volume yesterday, before trading was halted late in the
session. The announcement came after the close of trading
yesterday.
   National over-the-counter trading in United Banks was
halted late in the session. At that point, the stock was
trading at $20, up 1 1/8 from Monday's close.
   While the stock seems likely to climb today, yesterday's
closing price values United Banks at about $306 million.
   The state of Colorado will open to nationwide interstate
banking in January. United Banks, the state's largest holding
company with assets of $5.9 billion, disclosed in April that
it has held talks with out-of-state banking companies
interested in a possible acquisition aimed at gaining entry
to the state. Norwest, with assets of about $26.7 billion,
was among those identified by United Banks as discussing an
acquisition.
   Norwest currently has banking operations in Minnesota,
Wisconsin, Indiana, Illinois, Iowa, Nebraska, North Dakota,
South Dakota, Montana, and Arizona, and it recently reached a
definitive agreement to acquire Wyoming National Bancorp.,
its first bank in that state. Norwest, which in May paid $215
million to acquire First Interstate Corp. of Wisconsin has
made it clear that it intends to pursue further growth
through acquisition.
   United Banks of Colorado has a book value, or
shareholders' equity, of $26.47 a share. Acquisitions of
financially healthy financial institutions typically involve
a price in excess of book value, which suggests that any
Norwest proposal for United Banks would cost it upwards of
$400 million.
</TEXT>
