<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Former Governor
   Of West Virginia
   Gets Prison Term
   ----
   By Alecia Swasy
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   CHARLESTON, W.Va. -- Former West Virginia Gov. Arch A.
Moore Jr. was sentenced yesterday to five years and 10 months
in prison and was fined $170,000 for a scheme to extort money
from a coal operator and buy votes.
   The 67-year-old Mr. Moore, a three-term Republican
governor, pleaded guilty in April to charges of extortion,
obstruction of justice, and tax and mail fraud. He faced a
maximum penalty of 36 years in prison and fines of as much as
$1.2 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   It's not clear whether Mr. Moore will appeal. He couldn't
be reached for comment.
   Attorneys for Mr. Moore had asked to withdraw the guilty
plea, saying the former governor was rushed into his plea.
But federal Judge Walter Hoffman denied the request Monday.
The former governor remains free on bond until July 31, when
he is scheduled to report to a minimum-security prison in
Petersburg, Va.
   Michael W. Carey, a U.S. attorney in West Virginia, called
the sentence significant and proof that even former West
Virginia governors go to jail if they "violate the public
trust."
   The judge sentenced Mr. Moore to concurrent terms of five
years for extortion, six months for mail fraud and two years
for each of two charges of tax fraud. In addition, he was
sentenced to 10 months in prison on the obstruction of
justice charge.
   Prosecutors say Mr. Moore illegally diverted $100,000 in
state funds to his 1984 election campaign, which his
supporters used to buy votes from residents in southern West
Virginia counties.
   The extortion charge relates to a scheme in which he
agreed to use his influence as governor to refund $2.3
million from the state's black-lung fund to a coal operator.
In return, the coal operator agreed to offer Mr. Moore 25% of
the refund in kickbacks, according to the indictments by the
Charleston grand jury.
   The black-lung fund is a coal industry-funded pool of
money that provides payments to disabled miners who suffer
from the disease.
   The tax fraud counts allege that Mr. Moore filed false
campaign finance statements and tax returns in 1984 and 1985.
The obstruction of justice charge related to Mr. Moore's
alleged attempt to influence the testimony of two witnesses
during the investigation.
   Mr. Moore served as governor from 1969 to 1977 and from
1985 to 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900711-0052
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900711-0052.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   FDIC Said to Mull
   Filing Civil Charges
   Against Neil Bush
</HL>
<DATE>
07/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. is
considering filing civil charges against President Bush's son
Neil and other former officials of a Colorado thrift, but a
final decision hasn't been made yet, an agency spokesman
said.
   Neil Bush, a Denver oil businessman, was an outside
director of Silverado Banking Savings &amp; Loan Association,
which failed in late 1988 at an expected cost to the
government of $1 billion. The Office of Thrift Supervision
has charged him in an administrative action with violating
conflict-of-interest rules as a Silverado director. Mr. Bush
has denied any wrongdoing.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The FDIC routinely files civil charges against directors
and officers of failed institutions, as well as outside
attorneys and accountants, in cases where the government bank
and thrift insurance funds suffer a loss. The agency
typically brings charges of negligence and breach of
fiduciary duty to the institution, seeking to cover its
losses. Banks and thrifts usually carry insurance for their
officers and directors to protect them from such suits.
   ABC News reported last night that the FDIC is about to
file a $200 million civil suit against Mr. Bush and other
former Silverado officials, but the FDIC spokesman, said "no
final decision" has been made on whether to bring a suit.
High-level officials at the FDIC confirmed that a final
decision hasn't been made, but one person said a decision
"isn't too far off."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900711-0051
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900711-0051.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Commodities:
   Oil Prices Advance Due to Anticipation
   Of Cut in World Petroleum Oversupply
   ----
   By James Tanner
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C4
</SO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
PETROLEUM (PET)
COMMODITY MARKETS FOR METALS (MIN)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Oil prices rallied on anticipation of a reduction in the
world's oversupply of petroleum.
   Crude oil prices were up as much as 50 cents a barrel,
enough in some cases to offset all the declines of recent
days. On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the futures price
of crude oil for August delivery rose 36 cents a barrel to
$16.94.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Although there was debate over the likely duration of the
rally, oil analysts attributed the upturn to two major
factors. These were expectations that the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries finally may curb its
overproduction and anticipation that the latest report by the
American Petroleum Institute would show reduced U.S. crude
supplies.
   Little new information regarding OPEC output prospects
came out of yesterday's meeting of Persian Gulf oil ministers
in Saudi Arabia, where King Fahd is taking a more active role
in efforts to restore stability to oil prices. But the API
statistics, released after trading closed, showed that
drawdowns in U.S. crude inventories last week were more
bullish than expected, totaling nearly 3.7 million barrels.
   Gasoline inventories also fell by 1.7 million barrels last
week, about in line with industry projections. Meanwhile,
fuel futures were stronger yesterday with unleaded gasoline
for August delivery rising 1.01 cents a gallon to 57.86
cents.
   One factor in the firming market was an interruption in
supplies of methyl tertiary butyl ether from Arco Chemical
Co. The company had to reduce deliveries of the high-octane
gasoline additive after last week's explosion at its Houston
plant.
   Still, strength in the gasoline market helped propel U.S.
crude oil prices higher. Also, some U.S. refiners increased
their field postings for the benchmark West Texas
Intermediate crude by 50 cents a barrel to $15.75.
   Shahrokh Nikkhah, a senior vice president with
Prudential-Bache Securities, has turned "cautiously bullish"
on oil prices as a result of this week's upturn. "The $18.50
to $20 level is definitely in sight" for the near-term crude
contract on the New York Mercantile Exchange, he said. "I'm
looking for a move up to the $20 level after the July 25 OPEC
meeting," he added.
   But some others don't believe prices have bottomed yet.
"Prices have every prospect of remaining under pressure" at
least for two more months, said Peter Gignoux, manager of the
Shearson Lehman Hutton international energy desk in London.
   In other markets yesterday:
                                                                                                       

   LIVESTOCK and MEATS: As expected, the weekly cold storage
report showed lower-than-normal movement of pork bellies out
of storage, producing a decline in prices of pork belly
futures contracts. Pork bellies are used to make bacon. The
report showed a net movement of 2.9 million pounds of bellies
out of cold storage outside Chicago. That compares with a net
of as much as 4.6 million pounds a year earlier and a 10-year
average net at this time of about four million pounds.
Analysts don't think demand for bacon will keep pace with the
supply of fresh pork bellies. Higher-than-normal slaughter
levels have increased the supply of fresh bellies at a time
when demand for pork is sluggish.
                                                                                                       

   COPPER: Futures prices extended Monday's declines.
September delivery copper was off 0.60 cent a pound at
$1.1675. Traders viewed the decline as a reaction to an
overbought market, in which prices over the past two weeks
rose about 13 cents on unexpected developments. Meanwhile,
one analyst said a cave-in at the El Teniente mine in Chile
last week may cause a loss of 18,000 tons of refined copper
production. Yesterday's price decline occurred even though
London Metal Exchange warehouse stocks of copper were
reported to have declined by 2,325 tons to 51,225 tons, and
Commodities Exchange stocks were off 965 tons to 19,313 tons.
Fred Demler of PaineWebber observed that world-wide mine
production of copper was off 3 1/2% in March and April from
the same months last year. Also, he noted, shipments of
copper world-wide were up 10% in the first four months of the
year from a year earlier. However, he expects demand to
soften later in the year.
                                                                                                       

   PRECIOUS METALS: Gold futures prices declined moderately
on Middle Eastern selling, while silver was slightly higher
and platinum edged lower. August delivery gold was off $2.80
an ounce at $357.10. September silver ended with a gain of
one cent an ounce at $4.875. October platinum was off $1.10
an ounce at $488.90. Selling of gold, thought to be by the
same Middle Eastern interests that caused prices to break
sharply on several recent occasions triggered early price
weakness yesterday. Jeffrey Nichols, president of American
Precious Metals Advisors Ltd., Toronto, observed that while
the amount of bullion sold didn't appear to be significant,
traders are so nervous about the Middle Eastern selling that
they tend to liquidate holdings as soon as it develops.
</TEXT>
