<HL>
   Schering-Plough
   Announces Program
   For Early Retirement
</HL>
<DATE>
07/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   SGP
</CO>
<LP>
   MADISON, N.J. -- Schering-Plough Corp. announced a
temporary program that may induce early retirements, at a
pretax cost projected at "less than $15 million."
   The drug maker said the program won't affect earnings
materially. The company said it continues to project that per
share earnings will rise 18% to 20% this year. For 1989, the
company had net income of $471.3 million, or $4.18 a share,
on sales of $3.16 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Schering offered enhanced pensions to nearly 900 U.S.
employees who are 55 years or older with at least 10 years of
service. An undisclosed number of foreign employees received
comparable offers.
   The program, available until Aug. 10, gives retiring
employees an extra five years of age and length of service
for purposes of calculating pension benefits. That means
bigger pensions.
   The program applies retroactively to employees who retired
on or after last Dec. 31, the company said.
   Though it's costly in the short term to induce
retirements, many companies do so in order to lower long-term
head counts or payroll costs. Retiring workers often can be
replaced with younger, lower-paid workers, and in some cases
companies manage to get along without any replacements.
   Because of divestitures and cost-cutting moves, Schering's
head count has declined in recent years. A company spokesman
said there were 21,300 employees at the end of 1989, down
from 25,000 five years earlier. Schering said its retirement
incentives "may serve to further streamline the
organization."
   Schering closed at $48.125, down $1.25, in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading yesterday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900711-0026
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900711-0026.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Oracle Systems Corp.
   Reports a 58% Rise
   For Fiscal 4th Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
07/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<CO>
   ORCL
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
SOFTWARE (SOF)
</IN>
<LP>
   BELMONT, Calif. -- Oracle Systems Corp. posted a 58%
increase in fourth-quarter earnings after a disappointing
third quarter.
   Oracle said net income for the quarter ended May 31 was a
record $53 million, or 39 cents a share, compared with $33.5
million, or 25 cents a share, in the year-ago quarter.
Revenue was up 55% to a record $334.4 million from $215.9
million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The results are in contrast to the software company's flat
income growth in the third quarter, when Oracle broke a
five-year streak of rapid growth. The poor results caused its
stock to plunge 31% to $17.5 in one day. The stock began
climbing again in May, closing at $22.375, up 87.5 cents, in
national over-the-counter trading yesterday. The
fourth-quarter results were announced after the close of
trading.
   Oracle attributed the improved earnings, in part, to
improved cash flow and stronger-than-expected cash
collections for the quarter. Last March, the company blamed
its third-quarter debacle on accounting glitches and said it
would resume high growth in the fourth quarter. The flat
third quarter shook Wall Street out of a long love affair
with Oracle, which had quarterly net growth rates in 1989
ranging from 65% to 84%.
   For the fiscal year, Oracle said, net income was up 44% to
$117.4 million, or 86 cents a share, from $81.8 million, or
61 cents a share the previous fiscal year. Revenue increased
66% to $971 million from $584 million.
</TEXT>
