<HL>
   Technology:
   Encore Computer
   To Post Sizable Loss
   For Second Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
07/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   ENCC
</CO>
<LP>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. -- Encore Computer Corp. said it
expects to report a significant second-quarter loss. The
company also said it plans to lay off about 130 employees
from its staff of 1,825 workers.
   Encore, after years of struggling, appeared to be poised
for a turnaround in April 1989, when it acquired Gould Inc.'s
computer business from Nippon Mining Co. of Japan. At a
stroke, Encore increased its sales sixfold, acquired a big
presence in Europe, and quintupled its sales force to 165
people.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Yesterday, however, Encore's chairman and chief executive
officer, Kenneth G. Fisher, said that a revenue shortfall and
restructuring costs linked to new product introductions would
result in a sizable loss for the second quarter.
   The company declined to estimate the loss, saying it would
report final results in about two weeks. For the year-earlier
period, Encore had a net loss of $14.9 million, or 48 cents a
share, on revenue of $41.5 million.
   The new products are Encore's Seahawk and Gemini computer
systems, used primarily in flight simulators to train
military and commercial pilots. A company spokesman said the
revenue shortfall stemmed from a gap in sales as the company
moved to bring the new products to market. The Seahawk
computers, the spokesman said, are now being shipped to
customers, and the Gemini systems will start to be shipped in
the fourth quarter.
   The restructuring costs, Encore said, would result in the
layoff of about 130 people. The company spokesman said the
cutbacks will be made "across the board," in such departments
as manufacturing, finance and customer service.
   Despite the setback in the second quarter, Mr. Fisher,
citing the company's focus on its new products, said:
"Revenue could return to profitable levels in the third
quarter."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900711-0002
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900711-0002.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Canadian Court Says
   Tribunal Can't Cite
   Firms for Contempt
</HL>
<DATE>
07/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA C
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
AUTO PARTS AND EQUIPMENT INCLUDING TIRES (AUP)
</IN>
<LP>
   OTTAWA -- The Canadian Federal Appeal Court ruled that
Canada's Competition Tribunal doesn't have the power to
punish for contempt those who fail to comply with its orders.
   The tribunal, which was established in 1986, hears
competition cases and issues orders against anti-competitive
practices. The agency's jurisdiction was challenged by
Chrysler Canada Ltd., a unit of Chrysler Corp.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Canada was summoned before the tribunal for
alleged contempt of a tribunal order requiring the company to
supply auto parts to Richard Brunet Co., a Montreal concern.
It appealed the contempt case to the Federal Appeal Court,
claiming that the tribunal didn't have the jurisdiction to
punish for contempt.
   The court, in granting Chrysler Canada's appeal, said it
might be desirable for the tribunal to have the power to
punish for contempt. But the court said "it seems that
Parliament thought otherwise" when it passed legislation
establishing the tribunal in June 1986. The tribunal's
members include Federal Court judges and experts in such
fields as business and economics.
   The federal government's Bureau of Competition Policy,
which brought the case against Chrysler Canada before the
Competition Tribunal, said it was studying the court ruling
and would issue a statement later.
   The appeal court's decision is the Competition Tribunal's
second jurisdictional setback this year. In April, the Quebec
Superior Court ruled unconstitutional various operations of
the tribunal and certain merger provisions of the federal
Competition Act. The Quebec Superior Court ruling has been
appealed to the Quebec Court of Appeal by the Bureau of
Competition Policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900711-0001
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900711-0001.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Casino Analyst Files
   Claims Against Firm,
   Trump Over Firing
</HL>
<DATE>
07/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<CO>
   X.TMP
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Marvin Roffman, the casino analyst who lost
his job after making critical remarks about the financial
prospects for Donald Trump's Taj Mahal casino, has taken
legal action against both his former firm and Mr. Trump.
   Mr. Roffman filed an arbitration claim for wrongful
discharge against his former employer, Janney Montgomery
Scott, a securities firm owned by Penn Mutual Life Insurance
Co. The claim is being brought before a New York Stock
Exchange arbitration unit.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Roffman also is suing Mr. Trump in a Pennsylvania
federal court alleging that Mr. Trump interfered with Mr.
Roffman's employment by threatening to sue Janney Montgomery
unless Mr. Roffman publicly apologized for his remarks about
the Taj Mahal.
   For each action, Mr. Roffman is seeking compensatory
damages in excess of $1 million, plus unspecified punitive
damages. He also is seeking reinstatement by Janney
Montgomery Scott.
   On March 20, the day Mr. Roffman's negative comments about
the casino appeared in this newspaper, Mr. Trump wrote a
letter to Norman Wilde Jr., president of Janney Montgomery,
stating: "I am now planning to institute a major lawsuit
against your firm unless Mr. Roffman makes a major public
apology or is dismissed."
   Mr. Roffman first sent an apologetic letter to Mr. Trump
but withdrew it the next day, saying: "I retract the letter."
That day, Mr. Roffman was fired.
   Mr. Trump's attorney denied the casino owner and developer
had anything to do with Mr. Roffman's termination.
   An attorney for Janney Montgomery said Mr. Roffman was
fired for repudiating a letter to Mr. Trump apologizing for
his remarks about the Taj Mahal. The attorney said the letter
was written by Mr. Roffman after his supervisor warned him,
in writing, not to send it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
